      commentary: `This verse contains one of the central ethical questions of the Gita, asked by Arjuna before Krishna has spoken a word of philosophy: if we can see something is wrong, shouldn't we simply not do it?\n\nThe logic is clean and intuitive: we see the harm, we have the choice, therefore we should choose not to harm. Most ethical reasoning in daily life works exactly this way. But the Gita exists precisely because this apparently simple logic sometimes encounters a situation where it cannot be cleanly applied.\n\nKrishna will not tell Arjuna that he is wrong to value dharma or to care about the destruction of the family. He will show Arjuna a larger frame — one in which the situation looks different, in which the self is larger, in which action and non-action have different meanings. But the question asked here is honest, and it deserves the honest answer the Gita spends sixteen chapters giving.`
