      commentary: `Aho bata — alas! This is grief speaking, not argument. The elaborate philosophical case Arjuna has been building dissolves here into a single cry of anguish. We are about to do something terrible. We. Not them. We.\n\nIn this moment, Arjuna turns the accusation inward. He has been talking about the Kauravas' greed and blindness. Now he sees the same thing at work on his own side: the desire for a kingdom, for pleasures, for what is rightfully ours — all dressed in the language of dharma but powered by the same greed he condemned in Duryodhana.\n\nThis self-awareness is both the most painful and the most important moment in Arjuna's collapse. He sees his own complicity. He is not simply a good person opposing a bad situation. He is implicated in the very thing he opposes. That recognition — more than the grief, more than the arguments — is what brings him to his knees.`
