      commentary: `The first chapter ends here, with one of the most important images in all of sacred literature: a great warrior sitting down on the floor of his chariot, his bow fallen, his arrows scattered, his mind overwhelmed with grief.\n\nVisṛjya — casting aside. Not accidentally dropping. Deliberately letting go. Arjuna doesn't stumble and fall. He makes a choice, however confused, to put down the weapon. It is the choice of a person who has reached the end of what their current understanding can support.\n\nŚoka-saṁvigna-mānasaḥ — his mind agitated and overwhelmed with grief. Saṁvigna means shaken, disturbed, troubled. The compound with śoka (grief) describes a mind that has been completely undone by sorrow. This is the state from which the entire Gita arises: total collapse, complete inability to act, the end of all the identity structures that had told Arjuna who he was and what he should do.\n\nKrishna has not yet spoken a word of teaching. He is watching. Waiting. The first thing the Gita asks of its reader is to sit in this collapse with Arjuna — to not rush to the answer, to feel the full weight of the question. Because only from here, from this broken-open place, can the teaching actually land.\n\nChapter 1 ends. The Gita truly begins.`
